  ('wall-ball-chipper-segment', 'Wall Ball Chipper Segment improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Sustained Capacity because the intended stress is repeatable wall-ball work under fatigue while maintaining posture, breathing, target accuracy, and safe mechanics.', 'Use late in the session after Prepare & Access, Movement Intelligence, Output, and main Capacity priorities.', 'Do not chase exhaustion after mechanics degrade. Missed targets, collapsed catches, and ugly squats are not better conditioning.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('medicine-ball-front-squat', 'Medicine Ball Front Squat improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the drill builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve that supports wall-ball performance.', 'Use in the Capacity/Resilience support block after skill or power work.', 'Do not confuse a support-strength drill with a conditioning challenge. Load and range should build positions, not ruin them.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('medicine-ball-thruster-no-release', 'Medicine Ball Thruster (No Release) improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the drill builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve that supports wall-ball performance.', 'Use in the Capacity/Resilience support block after skill or power work.', 'Do not confuse a support-strength drill with a conditioning challenge. Load and range should build positions, not ruin them.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('medicine-ball-clean-to-squat', 'Medicine Ball Clean to Squat improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Movement Intelligence because the main adaptation is coordination, timing, target recognition, spacing, and movement quality while the nervous system is fresh.', 'Use after a general warm-up and before heavy strength or conditioning.', 'Do not rush the progression into heavy balls, high targets, or timed sets before the athlete owns timing and catch mechanics.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('medicine-ball-squat-clean-to-wall-ball-shot', 'Medicine Ball Squat Clean to Wall Ball Shot improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Sustained Capacity because the intended stress is repeatable wall-ball work under fatigue while maintaining posture, breathing, target accuracy, and safe mechanics.', 'Use late in the session after Prepare & Access, Movement Intelligence, Output, and main Capacity priorities.', 'Do not chase exhaustion after mechanics degrade. Missed targets, collapsed catches, and ugly squats are not better conditioning.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('wall-ball-low-catch-position-hold', 'Wall Ball Low-Catch Position Hold improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds controlled receiving, bracing, trunk position, joint ownership, and durable positions rather than speed or conditioning.', 'Use in the Capacity/Resilience support block after skill or power work.', 'Do not turn controlled holds, catches, or bracing work into speed reps. The value is control under manageable stress.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('wall-ball-overhead-catch-prep', 'Wall Ball Overhead Catch Prep improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Prepare & Access because the drill improves readiness, access, activation, or position ownership before higher-intent work without creating meaningful fatigue.', 'Use early in Prepare & Access before higher-intent wall-ball work.', 'Do not add enough volume or load that a readiness drill becomes fatigue work.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('front-rack-reverse-lunge-with-med-ball', 'Front-Rack Reverse Lunge with Med Ball improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the drill builds strength, force production, tissue tolerance, and structural reserve that supports wall-ball performance.', 'Use in the Capacity/Resilience support block after skill or power work.', 'Do not confuse a support-strength drill with a conditioning challenge. Load and range should build positions, not ruin them.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('tall-kneeling-chest-pass-to-wall', 'Tall-Kneeling Chest Pass to Wall improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Output because the goal is high-intent throwing, power, speed of extension, or short acceleration with low volume and full recovery.', 'Use after a general warm-up and before heavy strength or conditioning.', 'Do not turn this into a high-rep wall-ball workout. Full rest and clean speed are the point.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('half-kneeling-chest-pass-to-wall', 'Half-Kneeling Chest Pass to Wall improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Output because the goal is high-intent throwing, power, speed of extension, or short acceleration with low volume and full recovery.', 'Use after a general warm-up and before heavy strength or conditioning.', 'Do not turn this into a high-rep wall-ball workout. Full rest and clean speed are the point.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.'),
  ('medicine-ball-dead-bug-pullover', 'Medicine Ball Dead Bug Pullover improves wall-ball performance by matching the constraint that matters most: squat organization, ball path, target accuracy, trunk stiffness, catching, breathing, or repeatability. The drill creates a clear coaching problem and lets the coach progress one variable at a time: ball load, target height, squat depth, speed, rest, complexity, or total volume.', 'Belongs in Resilience because the drill builds controlled receiving, bracing, trunk position, joint ownership, and durable positions rather than speed or conditioning.', 'Use in the Capacity/Resilience support block after skill or power work.', 'Do not turn controlled holds, catches, or bracing work into speed reps. The value is control under manageable stress.', 'Scale by reducing ball weight, target height, squat depth, throw speed, movement complexity, total reps, work duration, or conditioning density before increasing intensity. The quality gate decides progression.')
